==English==

===Etymology===
First attested [[w:1581|1581]], from Latin [[diatriba]], ''learned [[discussion]] or [[discourse]]'', from Greek [[diatribe]] ''[[pastime]], [[lecture]]'', literally ''a consuming; a wearing away (of time)'',  from [[dia-]], ''away'' + [[tribein]] ''to wear or rub''.

===Noun===
'''diatribe''' (''plural'' '''diatribes''')
# An abusive, bitter denunciation
# A speech or writing which bitterly denounces something
#:''The senator was prone to diatribes which could go on for more than an hour.''

===Quotes===

*'''1991''' Bill Crow, ''Jazz Anecdotes''
: "You know, it's all this racial '''diatribe''', and very strong language, screaming at the top of his lungs into the telephone." [http://books.google.com/books?ie=UTF-8&hl=en&vid=ISBN0195071336&id=vQAcHPucrD4C&pg=PA316&lpg=PA316&dq=diatribe&prev=http://books.google.com/books%3Fq%3Ddiatribe%26lr%3D%26start%3D50&sig=I8NiqX-4z_Pk3y617emdNE4a69E]


